# Git Workflow

Standard git practices for every project. Same branching model, same commit format, same PR process - regardless of team size or tech stack.

> All numeric values in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Commits (agent policy)

**ONLY create a git commit when the user explicitly says** done, ship, commit, or equivalent. Do not commit because the agent believes a feature is finished.

**Message format `[DEFAULT]`:** Conventional Commits - e.g. `feat(checkout): validate cart before payment`.

**Push / PR:** Only when the user requests. Do not push to remote unless asked.

---

## Branch Naming

**Principle:** Branch names must be categorized, descriptive, and machine-parseable. Pick a prefix convention and enforce it.

[REFERENCE] Common branch type prefixes:

```
Format: {type}/{short-description}

  feature/    - new functionality
  fix/        - bug fix
  hotfix/     - urgent production fix (branches from main)
  refactor/   - code improvement with no behavior change
  chore/      - tooling, deps, config, CI changes
  docs/       - documentation only
  test/       - adding or fixing tests
  experiment/ - throwaway exploration (never merged directly)

Examples:
  feature/search-filters
  fix/api-rate-limit
  hotfix/session-expiry-crash
  refactor/extract-data-pipeline
  chore/upgrade-typescript
  docs/api-authentication-guide
```

**Rules:**
- All lowercase, words separated by hyphens
- Max 50 characters for the description part
- Issue-tracker IDs in branch names are optional - some teams prefer `JIRA-123-feature-name` for automation; either style is fine, be consistent.
- Avoid working directly on `main` or `master` - use feature branches. Exception: repo hygiene commits and break-glass hotfixes with immediate review.

---

## Commit Messages

**Principle:** Commit messages follow a structured format so changelogs and release notes can be generated automatically.

[REFERENCE] Common commit type prefixes (Conventional Commits style):

```
Format:
  {type}: {short description}

  {optional body - explain WHY, not WHAT}

  {optional footer - references, breaking changes}

  feature:   - new functionality
  fix:       - bug fix
  refactor:  - code change with no behavior change
  chore:     - tooling, deps, config
  docs:      - documentation
  test:      - tests
  style:     - formatting only (no logic change, no branch needed - commit directly)
  perf:      - performance improvement (use refactor/ or feature/ branch)
```

**Examples:**

```
feature: add secure token verification flow

Sends a time-limited verification link; token is hashed before storage
to prevent DB-leak exploitation.
```

```
fix: prevent duplicate form submission on rapid clicks

The submit button was not disabled during the API call,
allowing multiple records to be created.
```

```
refactor: extract computation logic into shared pipeline

Three routes duplicated the same shared computation logic.
Centralizing it reduces drift and makes testing easier.
```

```
chore: upgrade dependencies to latest and fix deprecated calls
```

**Rules:**
- Subject line: imperative mood ("add", "fix", "remove" - NOT "added", "fixes", "removing")
- Subject line: max 72 characters
- Subject line: no period at the end
- Body: wrap at 80 characters
- Body: explain WHY the change was made, not what changed (the diff shows what)
- One logical change per commit (don't bundle unrelated changes)
- Never commit generated files, build artifacts, or secrets
- Never commit with `--no-verify` unless explicitly justified

