## Pull Request Process

### PR Title Format

Same as commit message format: `{type}: {short description}`

### PR Body Template

```markdown
## Summary
- What this PR does (1-3 bullet points)

## Changes
- List of significant changes

## How to Test
1. Step-by-step testing instructions
2. Include edge cases to verify

## Screenshots / Video
(if UI changes - REQUIRED for frontend PRs)

## Checklist
- [ ] Code follows project naming conventions
- [ ] No non-idiomatic abbreviations in variable/function names (see naming.md)
- [ ] Loading states for all async operations
- [ ] Error handling covers failure paths
- [ ] Responsive layout tested (if applicable)
- [ ] Configuration options tested (if applicable)
- [ ] No console.log left in code
- [ ] Types are correct (no `any` without justification)
```

### PR Rules

1. **Keep PRs focused** - aim for under 500 lines changed. Mechanical refactors, dependency lockfiles, generated code, and i18n string dumps may be larger; what matters is "one logical change."
2. **One concern per PR** - don't mix a feature with a refactor
3. **Self-review first** - read your own diff before requesting review
4. **No merge without review** - at least 1 approval (solo projects: self-review with a checklist)
5. **Pick a merge strategy per project** (squash, rebase, or merge commits) and be consistent. Teams may use merge commits for long-lived branches and squash for features.
6. **Delete branch** after merge (keep the repo clean)
7. **CI must pass** before merge - emergency bypasses require a follow-up fix PR within the same day
8. **Resolve all comments** before merging (don't merge with open threads)

